So I'm gonna try to explain how this works by first telling you how it doesn't work

00:22:51.359 --> 00:22:57.040
This is how when I first heard about this functionality, this is how I imagined it working, but it is not how it works

00:22:58.119 --> 00:23:03.520
So one example of something that a pure LLM cannot do an LLM is is just a model

00:23:03.520 --> 00:23:08.760
It can't get the current weather, right? You need a weather service for that

00:23:08.959 --> 00:23:14.439
So in this case, let's say we have a user as the assistant. What's the weather right now at Fenway Park?

00:23:15.119 --> 00:23:17.719
When I heard that there was something called tool calling that lets

00:23:18.239 --> 00:23:24.439
LLMs access other systems what I imagined is somehow we would be teaching the assistant to reach out to open weather org

00:23:24.479 --> 00:23:26.719
it's a fictional service, but just pretend and

00:23:28.280 --> 00:23:29.560
Call

00:23:29.560 --> 00:23:31.839
Give me the weather for 0 2 2 1 5

00:23:32.640 --> 00:23:34.640
That's the zip code where Fenway Park is

00:23:35.239 --> 00:23:40.400
Open weather would return the data as JSON and then the assistant would

00:23:40.719 --> 00:23:46.560
Incorporate that JSON into its response and say 65 degrees and sunny. Okay. This is how I imagine it working

00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:48.560
But this is not how it works

00:23:50.640 --> 00:23:52.640
Instead it works like this

00:23:52.839 --> 00:23:59.319
The user asks the question. What's the weather right now at Fenway Park and it includes along with that request a

00:24:00.160 --> 00:24:07.280
Description of a tool called get current weather. So it's not passing code. It is just passing metadata about a function

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:09.719
It's saying the name of this function is get current weather

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:14.880
It takes a single argument that argument is a zip code and it's a string

00:24:15.439 --> 00:24:19.839
So the assistant instead of answering with what the weather is it?

00:24:20.160 --> 00:24:24.319
Instead responds saying I would like to call this tool that you said was available

00:24:24.839 --> 00:24:31.439
Called get current weather 0 2 2 1 5 and it is actually the responsibility of the client not the server

00:24:31.959 --> 00:24:37.560
To go off and perform this request against openweather.org or however else it wants to

00:24:38.239 --> 00:24:40.439
Fulfill the task of getting the current weather

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:46.280
When a response is received then the user continues the conversation

00:24:46.520 --> 00:24:52.479
By taking this response that the assistant asked for and sending it to the assistant and the assistant now

00:24:52.479 --> 00:24:58.439
it has the original question it sees the request that it sent and it sees a response that came back from the user and

00:24:59.239 --> 00:25:04.640
Therefore now it's able to actually give a proper response back to the client

00:25:05.599 --> 00:25:11.800
Incorporating this this data. So it seems a lot more complicated, but is actually much simpler

00:25:12.959 --> 00:25:14.319
basically

00:25:14.319 --> 00:25:21.920
Just just to recap the user asks the assistant a question and includes metadata for tools or functions that are available

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:29.359
The assistant asks the user to invoke a tool on its behalf and passes the arguments that should be used

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:32.280
the user invokes the tool and

00:25:32.640 --> 00:25:39.000
Returns the output to the assistant which the assistant can then use as context for its final response

00:25:40.119 --> 00:25:47.140
It turns out this is an incredibly general and powerful way to extend the capabilities of these

00:25:47.500 --> 00:25:52.859
Of these assistants and anytime you hear the word agent used which is a lot these days

00:25:53.420 --> 00:26:00.140
Just know that all of that is made possible by creating these tools and giving LLMs access to them

